commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

commits.author: Sergio Costas
commits.message:
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.

commits.author: Carlos Nihelton
commits.message:
fix(CI): Use tar-based images and no longer rely on empty tarballs  (#141)

This project used to rely on registering empty tarballs as rootfses to
speed up some tests that didn't depend on the final state of a
registered distro, a nifty trick because registration was almost
instantaneous. But it's been a while since WSL no longer supports that,
as it validates the tarball contents.

So from now on, unless we're leveraging gowslmock, we use the new
tar-based images, sourced from daily builds and cached for fast
subsequent accesses (instead of using the appx's sourced form MS Store).

There seems to be some pessimisation in the test duration comparing to
previous successful runs:
https://github.com/ubuntu/GoWSL/actions/workflows/qa.yaml?query=is%3Asuccess
I'd say that's acceptable, though subject to further improvements in the
test code itself (or perhaps leveraging smaller images - thus quicker
registrations).

ci: Add TiCS token existence check (#260)

In certain contexts, such as when the workflow-triggering actor is
Dependabot or if running from a fork, secrets are not available. While
the codecov action handles this without causing a job failure, TiCS does
result in a job failure. Thus, here we introduce a conditional check
that skips TiCS if the secret is not set and instead log a warning.

By handling this in the `tics-condition` step, we also skip some then
unnecessary setup steps that have additional costs.

commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
ci(qa): Add concurrency group to prevent overlapping runs in process-coverage job (#259)

When multiple PRs are merged in quick succession, it is not uncommon for
TiCS in QServer mode to be triggered concurrently. However, this causes
a subsequent job failure, as only one QServer session can be active at a
time. Thus, here we implement concurrency groups for the
`process-coverage` job that forces only one concurrent run per
triggering ref.

This does mean that we also limit the job in PRs, but this is less of an
issue as we skip TiCS in those cases, allowing for the job to run
relatively quickly.

We don't enable job cancellation in case that results in bad behavior
with TiCS, and also because cancellations may cause unnecessary job
failures.

commits.author: Carlos Nihelton
commits.message:
feat: Adds an integration test workflow (#27)

Looks like we can go quite far with GitHub hosted runners these days
(since they made large runners generally available).

I devised an integration test workflow for `wsl-setup` that:
- Downloads and caches the daily-live/current image from
cdimages.ubuntu.com
- In parallel, it builds the wsl-setup debian package from git
- When above are done:
  * sets up a WSL instance,
  * installs the deb built by CI, 
  * clean up cloud-init state, 
  * writes some cloud-init user data, 
* does some actions to prevent the test from being stuck in case
cloud-init fails,
* runs the initial setup via WSL itself (with just `wsl -d DISTRO`) and
* runs some assertions based on the results of having wsl-setup
installed.
  
To support development time, part of the assertions are placed in a
separate shell script that we can run inside a VM, LXD container or WSL
instance at development time (though some can only pass on WSL),
assertions which are really coupled to the contents of the package, thus
we should pay attention to them when changing the package. Unfortunately
I'm not bold enough to put those assertions in an override_build step of
debian/rules because I that could result in unnecessary breakages.

My image caching system saves more bandwidth than time. I was pleased to
see that CI was taking less than 30s to download a WSL image (building
the deb takes much longer, there's probably some caching opportunity in
the callee side?). The cache key is the image checksum read from the
SHA256SUMS file hosted aside from the image. I had to learn a few tricks
to make the cache working cross OSes.

The WSL instance is created from the cached image with `wsl --install
--from-file ... --no-launch ...` so we can further customise it with
other `wsl -d DISTRO -- <COMMANDS>` without those counting as if the
OOBE script was run, that is, WSL keeps track of that instance as still
non-initialized.

This whole scheme allows us to:
- claim that the package builds both source and binary outputs
- claim that the installed package behaves as expected on a target
- smoke test the latest images, preventing late breakages if breaking
changes appear in them without us noticing.

commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

commits.author: Sergio Costas
commits.message:
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.

commits.author: Carlos Nihelton
commits.message:
feat: Adds an integration test workflow (#27)

Looks like we can go quite far with GitHub hosted runners these days
(since they made large runners generally available).

I devised an integration test workflow for `wsl-setup` that:
- Downloads and caches the daily-live/current image from
cdimages.ubuntu.com
- In parallel, it builds the wsl-setup debian package from git
- When above are done:
  * sets up a WSL instance,
  * installs the deb built by CI, 
  * clean up cloud-init state, 
  * writes some cloud-init user data, 
* does some actions to prevent the test from being stuck in case
cloud-init fails,
* runs the initial setup via WSL itself (with just `wsl -d DISTRO`) and
* runs some assertions based on the results of having wsl-setup
installed.
  
To support development time, part of the assertions are placed in a
separate shell script that we can run inside a VM, LXD container or WSL
instance at development time (though some can only pass on WSL),
assertions which are really coupled to the contents of the package, thus
we should pay attention to them when changing the package. Unfortunately
I'm not bold enough to put those assertions in an override_build step of
debian/rules because I that could result in unnecessary breakages.

My image caching system saves more bandwidth than time. I was pleased to
see that CI was taking less than 30s to download a WSL image (building
the deb takes much longer, there's probably some caching opportunity in
the callee side?). The cache key is the image checksum read from the
SHA256SUMS file hosted aside from the image. I had to learn a few tricks
to make the cache working cross OSes.

The WSL instance is created from the cached image with `wsl --install
--from-file ... --no-launch ...` so we can further customise it with
other `wsl -d DISTRO -- <COMMANDS>` without those counting as if the
OOBE script was run, that is, WSL keeps track of that instance as still
non-initialized.

This whole scheme allows us to:
- claim that the package builds both source and binary outputs
- claim that the installed package behaves as expected on a target
- smoke test the latest images, preventing late breakages if breaking
changes appear in them without us noticing.

---

UDENG-7866

commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

commits.author: Sergio Costas
commits.message:
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.

commits.author: Sergio Costas Rodriguez
commits.message:
Fix test

The test test_refresh_monitor failed to build because NULL was
being passed to the constructor, which has no parameters. This
happened when building in 25.10, but not in older systems,
because in them, GCC presumes that a function declared with ()
has an indeterminated number of parameters.

This has been fixed, and also "void" has been added to all the
functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is
always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

commits.message:
gnome-shell: Optimize the contrast of the dialog warnings

Dialog warnings were already a bit optimized, but now we take a step
further, since we can do composition we can find out the final
background color and then compute the correctly optimized text color

commits.author: Marco Trevisan (Treviño)
commits.message:
gnome-shell/yaru-colors: Optimize the contrast of the warning fg color

Now that we can use composition, it's possible!

commits.author: Marco Trevisan (Treviño)
commits.message:
sass-utils: Add a composite function

Sometimes we need to mix colors with different alpha on top of an opaque
color to know the final result, so we can do composition in sass and
figure out what is the final color

commits.author: Carlo Lobrano
commits.message:
Add support for communitheme (#4)

In 18.04, Yaru theme is still called Communitheme, then the special code
for toggling among the its three variants does not work.

This change takes into account the two possible names for Yaru theme and
clean the code up.
